editorialDecl.label: Editor's Note
editorialDecl.p: This is the coded edition of the second movement of K. 458. It is based on the first print edition, Sei quartetti per due violini, viola, e violoncello. Composti e Dedicati al Signor Giueppe Haydn, op. X, Vienna: Artaria, 1785.
Adjustments:

This source does not present any problems of textual gaps or unclear pitch. Most problems regard dynamics (presence/absence), and slurring (presence/absence and imprecision). The edition pursues the policy of a moderate adjustment guided by the following principles:
- Vertical adaptation between parts is possible but not mandatory.

- Adjustments can take place within a narrow range (one or two measures), depending on the musical context and situation, e.g. as a repetition of a pattern in the case of a sequence or a dialogue between instruments.
- Adjustment 'at a distance' is possible within some limitations, however, retroactive adjustments (from a later to an earlier instance) are excluded.
- The 'edited text' accepts inconsistent slurring between parts moving synchronously, in particular if the pattern is diachronically consistent within the individual part.
- The 'edited text' accepts the concept of variation between recurring and repeated sections and material.
Additions:

The 'edited text' adds only few dynamic markings, based to the immediate musical context. In accordance with 18th-century practice, there are no additional dynamics in stretches where the source does not present any dynamics leaving it at the discretion of the performer to use appropriate dynamics.
Conjectures:

Within the context of this edition, already existing notation element that are being shifted or reinterpreted are treated as conjectures. The position or value of the original sign is marked up (orig) together with the new value (corr). 'corr' is not to be understood unilaterally as (error) correction, but as an alternative to the reading of the source; if the reading of the source is indistinct, 'corr' may also serve as a means of clarification of an unclear reading.
Editorial normalizations:

Normalization follows formalized notational standards, the edition adopts some deliberately applied conventions for this particular text (e.g. non-slurring of grace notes) based on idiosyncrasis of the source.
Articulation:
As for the use of articulation, the edition follows the source in using uniquely strokes with the exception of dots over repeated notes in combination with a tie.
Readings and Markup:

The edition presents for all individual instances one accepted final reading which is 'the edition'. (Alternative and, according to the source, different readings are coded in the file and may have to be activated or visualized on demand.) However, sections that potentially pose particular editorial challenges are marked; a comment (annotation) categorized as 'DME-comment' may be available.
Genetic information:

All instances in the source that have been labelled 'unclear' are marked as such.
Certain observation regarding formal pecularities of the source may be reported in annotations that are categorized as 'DME-observation'.
These are individual considerations adopted for the 'edited text' of K. 458/02; for a full description of the general principles see the Editorial Guidelines of the DME Music Editions.
